.Dd March 29, 2026
.Dt SED 1
.Os Kayoko
.Sh NAME
.Nm sed
.Nd stream editor
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl n
.Ar script
.Op Ar file ...
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility is a stream editor that reads the specified
.Ar file
arguments (or standard input if none are given) and parses them according to a 
list of commands in the
.Ar script .
.Pp
The
.Nm
utility operates by maintaining a
.Em pattern space :
a buffer containing the current line being processed. The
.Ar script
is applied to the pattern space, and the resulting content is printed to 
standard output unless the
.Fl n
option is specified.
.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Fl n
Suppress the default output. Only lines explicitly addressed by a
.Ic p
command or modified by an
.Ic s
command with a print flag will be output.
.El
.Sh ADDRESSING
Commands within the
.Ar script
may be preceded by an address or a range of addresses. If no address is 
specified, the command is applied to every line.
.Bl -tag -width "addr1,addr2"
.It Ar n
Matches the n-th line of the input stream.
.It Ar addr1 , addr2
Matches a range of lines from
.Ar addr1
to
.Ar addr2
inclusive.
.El
.Sh COMMANDS
The following commands are currently supported:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It (addr1,addr2) Ic d
Delete the pattern space and immediately start the next cycle.
.It (addr1,addr2) Ic p
Print the pattern space to standard output.
.It (addr1,addr2) Ic s/re/replacement/g
Substitute
.Ar replacement
for the regular expression
.Ar re
in the pattern space. The
.Ic g
suffix indicates that all occurrences of the expression should be replaced.
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Ex -std
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr ed 1 ,
.Xr grep 1 ,
.Xr regex 7
